BarcodingR: an integrated r package for species identification using DNA barcodes

Ai-bing Zhang,

Summary

  1. Species identification via DNA barcodes has recently become an important and routine task in many biodiversity projects using DNA sequence data.
  2. Here, we present BarcodingR, an integrated software package that provides a comprehensive implementation of species identification methods, including artificial intelligence, fuzzy-set, Bayesian and kmer-based methods, that are not readily available in other packages.
  3. BarcodingR additionally provides new functions for barcode evaluation, barcoding gap analysis, delimitation comparison analysis, species membership analysis and consensus identification.
  4. Comparison with other barcoding methods using 11 empirical data sets indicates that on average, FZKMER (implemented in BarcodingR) and one extant barcoding method BRONX outperform all other methods examined in this study. Two other methods, BP and FZ (both implemented in BarcodingR), present similar performance as SVM and BLOG, respectively, and all display better performance than that of Jrip.
  5. The software of BarcodingR is open source under GNU General Public License and freely available for all major operating systems.

Introduction

DNA barcodes have been widely used in biodiversity and evolutionary studies for both terrestrial and aquatic metazoan animals and plants (Hebert, Ratnasingham & deWaard 2003b; Hebert et al. 2003a; Ward et al. 2005; Hajibabaei et al. 2006; Zhang et al. 2008, 2012a,b; Dinca et al. 2011; Dai et al. 2012; Jin et al. 2013; Frantine-Silva et al. 2015). Investigation into global biodiversity has been stimulated alongside accumulation of DNA barcode data, with the BOLD system (www.barcodinglife.org) now having DNA barcodes for more than 250 279 species globally and 4 649 254 barcodes in total (as of January 2, 2016). In this context, species identification using DNA barcodes and a comprehensive reference library has become a core task in biodiversity studies (Mitchell 2015; Saslis-Lagoudakis et al. 2015; Schmidt et al. 2015; Versteirt et al. 2015). Thus, barcoding methodology has advanced tremendously since the initiation of this venture in 2003 (Sarkar, Planet & Desalle 2008; Zhang et al. 2008, 2012a,b; Zhang & Savolainen 2009; Jones, Ghoorah & Blaxter 2011; Little 2011; Jin, He & Zhang 2012; van Velzen et al. 2012; Weitschek, Fiscon & Felici 2014). However, there are many valuable methods lacking user-friendly or non-commercial implementations, such as BP-based, fuzzy-set based methods and non-protein-coding barcoding.

Here, we present an integrated r software package, BarcodingR, for species identification using DNA barcodes that is designed to be user-friendly and runs on Microsoft Windows, Mac OSX and Linux. BarcodingR includes implementations of BP-based (Zhang et al. 2008; Zhang & Savolainen 2009), fuzzy-set based (Zhang et al. 2012b) and Bayesian species identification (Jin et al. 2013), and new/updated functions variously useful in barcode study such as barcode evaluation, kmer optimization (Kuksa & Pavlovic 2009; Polychronopoulos et al. 2014; Weitschek, Cunial & Felici 2015), DNA barcode gap analysis, species membership analysis, delimitation comparison analysis and consensus identification. The performance of BarcodingR, in comparison with several existing barcoding methods, was evaluated using 11 empirical data sets covering wide range of genetic variation from invertebrates to plants to vertebrates.

BarcodingR package

The ‘BarcodingR’ package is written in r language and was initially released on Github (https://github.com/zhangab2008/BarcodingR) and is now deposited in cran (https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/BarcodingR/index.html). BarcodingR relies on the r packages of ‘ape’ (Paradis, Claude & Strimmer 2004), ‘adegenet’ (Jombart 2008), ‘mclust’ (Fraley & Raftery 1999), ‘phyclust’ (Chen & Dorman 2010), ‘cclust’ (https://cran.r-project.org/), ‘pegas’ (Paradis 2010), ‘seqinr’ (Charif et al. 2005), ‘nnet’ (Ripley 1996), ‘e1071’ (https://cran.r-project.org/) and ‘spider’ (Brown et al. 2012).

The main functions of the BarcodingR package are listed in Table 1. Among them, three key species identification functions are included as follows: ‘barcoding.spe.identify’, ‘barcoding.spe.identify2’ and ‘bbsik’. The function barcoding.spe.identify makes species identification using protein-coding barcodes with different methods, including BP-based method (Zhang et al. 2008), fuzzy-set based method (Zhang et al. 2012b), Bayesian-based method (Jin et al. 2013), given reference and query DNA sequences. Correspondingly, barcoding.spe.identify contains the following options:
  1. bpNewTraining/bpNewTrainingOnly/bpUseTrained. With the option ‘bpNewTraining’, the function performs BP model training and species identification simultaneously. This is recommended for small-to-moderate scale data sets, for instance less than a thousand barcodes. In other situations, training BP model with the option ‘bpNewTrainingOnly’ and making species identification using option ‘bpUseTrained’ can be conducted separately at different time. Generally, the estimated model parameters are saved into a temporary file in the working folder and are loaded later on when running the function with the option ‘bpUseTrained’ to make species identification.
  2. fuzzyId. With the option ‘fuzzyId’, the function assign each potential identification an ‘FMF value’ in the range of 0–1, indicating likelihood of the assignment (Zhang et al. 2012b). To speed up identification, a KNN search algorithm (http://www.stats.ox.ac.uk/pub/MASS4/) is used instead of the MD algorithm (Zhang et al. 2012b) in the reference library search step for the current version of the function. To avoid potential false positives in cases of incomplete taxon coverage in the reference library, and to obtain a fast identification for relatively large-scale data sets, fuzzyId option is strongly recommended.
  3. Bayesian. Additionally, function barcoding.spe.identify provides species identification using Bayesian approach as well (Jin et al. 2013).

Besides the standard COI barcodes, non-coding makers such as ITS1 and ITS2 are widely used for both animals and plants (Adams et al. 2008; Bellemain et al. 2010; Dai et al. 2012). Multiple sequence alignment for such length variable markers can be problematic (Zhang et al. 2008, 2012b; Zhang & Savolainen 2009). Zhang et al. (2012a) proposed an alignment-free approach for species identification (Kuksa & Pavlovic 2009; Polychronopoulos et al. 2014; Weitschek, Cunial & Felici 2015), with implementation within the matlab environment. We here provide such an alignment-free kmer-based approach for non-coding barcode species identification (Zhang et al. 2012a). The algorithm firstly searches for potential kmer sets in the reference, calculates their frequencies for each reference sequence and finally obtains a kmer frequency matrix that can be used for model building in a fuzzy-set approach. After obtaining a kmer set for the references, a corresponding kmer frequency vector for queries can also be computed. Potential species memberships for each query can then be inferred using the KNN algorithm mentioned above. To achieve an optimal kmer length, we also include the function opitimize.kmer that returns an optimal length defined as that with maximal species identification success rate of the model. The kmer frequency matrix can be further used in other methods/functions, including the BP and fuzzy-set based methods.

Barcodes evaluation

On occasions, where more than one marker/barcode are used, one may wish to know which is preferable in species identification. A new function barcodes.eval (barcode1, barcode2, kmer1 = kmer1, kmer2 = kmer2) was developed to statistically evaluate two alternative markers according to ‘leave-one-out’ simulation, with an additional two-sample test for equality of proportions (Wilson 1927). The null hypothesis examined is that the species identification success rate is not statistically different between markers. The function returns the success rates of both markers and corresponding P values.

Barcoding gaps

Computing DNA barcoding gap is generally treated as one of typical DNA barcoding analysis (Meyer & Paulay 2005; Meier, Zhang & Ali 2008; Candek & Kuntner 2015). The distribution of pairwise genetic distance of interspecific and intraspecific genetic variation (generally measured in K2P genetic distance) is presented using the histogram plot in Fig. 1. The non-overlapping of interspecific and intraspecific genetic distance distribution is considered as the existence of barcoding gap that indicates clear species boundaries. The r function in package spider provides a way to present barcoding gaps (Brown et al. 2012), but see (Little, Knopf & Schulz 2013) for some critiques, we here report a new r function barcoding.gap to display DNA barcoding gaps alternatively. A full data set, instead of that with haplotypes only, is strongly recommended to be used to calculate barcoding gaps because shared haplotypes between different species may result in misleading barcoding gaps distribution.

Consensus of multiple identifications and comparison between two delimitations/identifications

Species identifications can be made with different approaches, such as fuzzy-set based (Zhang et al. 2012b), BP-based (Zhang et al. 2008) and Bayesian method (Munch et al. 2008; Hao, Jiang & Chen 2011; Jin et al. 2013). Choosing one of these options (‘fuzzyId’, ‘bpNewTraining’ and ‘Bayesian’) of the r function of barcoding.spe.identify can perform any of these identifications. However, one may need a consensus of all these identifications for the same query. We developed a new function consensus.identify to perform this task by taking several identifications with different methods as inputs. The function returns a data frame with identities of queries, consensus of different identifications and the number of votes.

In a typical DNA barcoding project, data analyses may interweave with those for DNA taxonomy (Pons et al. 2006; Talavera, Dinca & Vila 2013; Dellicour & Flot 2015). In the latter case, species delimitation based on barcodes is among the main and basic analysis (Pons et al. 2006; Talavera, Dinca & Vila 2013; Dellicour & Flot 2015). Species delimitation, named as MOTU, can be obtained with any of these methods, including GMYC (Pons et al. 2006), jMOTU (Jones, Ghoorah & Blaxter 2011) and ABGD (Puillandre et al. 2012). In most of these cases, one may be especially interested in the difference between species delimitation using MOTU and traditionally morphological classification of species. To this end, we developed an r function compare2delimitations which calculates the adjusted Rand index (Hubert & Arabie 1985), the numbers of matches, splits, merges of species between two delimitations, and corresponding percentages.

Comparison with other methods

Empirical data sets

We selected 11 published empirical DNA barcode data sets in the range from invertebrates to vertebrates to plants, covering a wide range of genetic variation of different DNA barcodes (Table 2, Appendix S2, Supporting Information). Most of these data sets have been used to evaluate a variety of DNA barcoding approaches (Jones, Ghoorah & Blaxter 2011; Little 2011; van Velzen et al. 2012; Zhang et al. 2012a,b; Weitschek, Fiscon & Felici 2014). Therefore, comparison among various methods implemented in BarcodingR and others becomes possible and easy using these data sets. Four additional insect data sets, one from butterfly and three from moths, were added to our analyses due to high proportion of insects barcoding data (www.barcodinglife.org). All these data sets can be readily classified into invertebrates, vertebrates and plants (Table 2, Appendix S2).

Vertebrates and plants

Vertebrate data sets consist of four data sets, bats (Clare et al. 2007), fish (Steinke et al. 2009), birds (Hebert et al. 2004) and amphibian (Smith, Poyarkov & Hebert 2008; Table 2, Appendix S2). The bat data set is composed of 840 COI barcodes from specimens belonging to 86 species, with a length of 659 bp. The fish data set is composed of 626 barcode sequences from specimens belonging to 82 species. The bird data set is composed of 1936 barcodes from individuals that belong to 575 species (Hebert et al. 2004). For the bird data set, we did not use the data set provided in the study of Weitschek, Fiscon & Felici (2014), where no taxon information was included. The amphibian data set includes 357 barcode sequences from 30 species (Smith, Poyarkov & Hebert 2008). The plant data set comprises 913 barcodes from 56 species (Dexter, Pennington & Cunningham 2010). In this data set, cpDNA trnTD intron and nrDNA Internally Transcribed Spacer (ITS) sequences were linked into a multilocus DNA barcodes of 1713–1771 nucleotides in total (van Velzen et al. 2012).

Invertebrates

Invertebrate data sets comprise six sub-datasets: gastropods (Cypraeidae; Meyer & Paulay 2005), fruit fly (Drosophila; Lou & Golding 2010), butterfly (Dinca et al. 2011), geometrid moth (Ratnasingham & Hebert 2013), Tibetan noctuid moth (Jin et al. 2013) and lappet moth (Dai et al. 2012). The sub-dataset of Cypraeidae, as one of the most extensively taxonomically studied marine gastropods, is composed of 2008 COI barcodes of 211 species (Meyer & Paulay 2005). The Drosophila data set was reported to have less between-species genetic variation than within-species divergence (Castillo et al. 2011). The data set consists of 615 COI barcode from 19 species. A complete DNA barcode data set for a country's butterfly fauna was recently reported (Dinca et al. 2011). This comprises the 180 species of butterflies in Romania (about one-third of the European butterfly fauna). Morphology and DNA barcodes of more than 1300 specimens, belonging to six butterfly families (Hesperiidae, Papilionidae, Pieridae, Lycaeridae, Riodinidae and Nymphalidae), were studied. We downloaded sequences from GenBank (accession numbers HQ003941–HQ005268; Dinca et al. 2011). The data set was cleaned by removing sequences with ambiguous sites, such as ‘Ns’, and those whose lengths were <648 bp. A total of 1235 sequences from 174 species remained (Table 2, Appendix S2). Sequence alignment used the program muscle (Edgar 2004) with the default setting. The sub-dataset of geometrid moth is composed of 649 COI barcodes from 301 species (Ratnasingham & Hebert 2013). Tibetan noctuid moth data set contains 320 COI barcodes which belongs to 71 moth species (Jin et al. 2013), whereas lappet moth data set consists of 97 ITS2 sequences from seven closely related pine moth species (Dai et al. 2012; Table 2, Appendix S2).

Performance comparisons

To demonstrate the performance of the main DNA barcoding approaches implemented in package BarcodingR, we compared our methods, FZKMER, BP and FZ (all implemented in BarcodingR), with two typical diagnostic methods, BLOG (Weitschek et al. 2013) and BRONX (Little 2012), and two supervised DNA barcodes methods (Jrip and SVM; Hall et al. 2009), using 11 empirical data sets mentioned above. These methods have been reported to have excellent performance in species identification with DNA barcodes in comparative studies of DNA barcoding methods (Little 2011; van Velzen et al. 2012; Zhang et al. 2012b; Weitschek, Fiscon & Felici 2014). The sequences of the empirical data sets are divided into a reference set (80% per species), including the sequences with a priori assigned species membership, a query set (20% per species), comprising also the DNA barcode sequences with an a priori assigned species names (but not considered by the algorithm) for an evaluation of the classification success. The divisions of reference and query set are performed according to the same data splits present in previous works (Weitschek, Fiscon & Felici 2014) when possible for allowing a comparison of the classification results.

On average, significantly different species identification accuracies were detected with a total of 2051 queries taken from 11 empirical data sets (Fig. 2a). FZKMER (implemented in BarcodingR) and BRONX (Little 2012) outperform all other methods by as high as 98·05% and 97·55% species identification accuracies [95% confidence intervals (CI): 97·33–98·59% for FZKMER; 96·77–98·17% for BRONX; Fig. 2a]. BP (implemented in BarcodingR) and SVM (SMO, implemented in weka; Hall et al. 2009) present the 2nd best performance with a 91·81% (95% CI: 90·52–92·94%) and 89·66% (95% CI: 88·25–90·93%) of success rates (Fig. 2a). Jrip (Hall et al. 2009) obtains the lowest species identification accuracy of 77·72% (95% CI: 75·84–79·49%) among all methods examined in this study (Fig. 2a). FZ (implemented in BarcodingR) achieves a similar mean species identification success rate (87·66%, 95% CI: 86·15–89·04%) to that of BLOG (87·86%, 95% CI: 86·35–89·23%, Fig. 2a).

Although the accuracy performance of BLOG and JRIP is lower, they both provide the investigator with a human readable classification model.

Detailed species identification accuracy for each empirical data set with different barcoding methods is presented in Fig. 2b,c. For most of empirical data sets, such as amphibian, bats, fish, plants (inga), butterfly, Drosophila, gastropods and noctuid moth, six barcoding methods achieve similar species identification accuracy (Fig. 2b,c). For two empirical data sets, birds and geometrid moth, significantly variable species identification success rates, are obtained using different methods, with FZKMER and BRONX performing as the best two methods and Jrip the worst one (Fig. 2b,c).

Complete example of application

In this section, we report a complete example of the BarcodingR software application.

File formats: input and output

Most of functions in BarcodingR take objects of DNAbin class as inputs. To obtain DNAbin objects, users should prepare two fasta format files, corresponding to reference and query sequences, respectively, and these two data sets are read into r using function read.dna in r package ape (Paradis, Claude & Strimmer 2004) or another r function fasta2DNAbin in package adegenet (http://adegenet.r-forge.r-project.org/). Please note that the reference data set must contain taxon information with a special format like ‘>seqID, species_names’, for instance, ‘>seq1, Dendrolimus_punctatus’, or ‘>seq1, Lasiocampidae_Dendrolimus_punctatus’, whereas query data set can be in general fasta format. The main species identification functions in BarcodingR return a list, containing queIDs, identified species, and bp.probilities/FMF values, outputs can be written into a file using the function save.ids, which takes object of ‘BarcodingR’ class as inputs.

How to run

Here, we provide examples of utilities of the main functions in BarcodingR using included data sets. First, one should load the package and example data.

  • library(BarcodingR)

  • data(TibetanMoth)

  • data(pineMothCOI)

  • data(pineMothITS1)

  • data(pineMothITS2)

barcoding.spe.identify

The method of function barcoding.spe.identify includes five options, three of which especially designed for BP-based species identification (Zhang et al. 2008; Zhang & Savolainen 2009). The first is ‘bpNewTraining’ that is able to make direct species identification by taking two main arguments ref and que for relatively small data sets (<500 samples suggested). If the COI barcode data sets contain more than 500 samples, it is strongly recommended that the option ‘bpNewTrainingOnly’ should be used first to train the BP model. Species identification then is made using the option ‘bpUseTrained’ in the second run of the function. Additionally, the function provides two other options ‘fuzzyId’ and ‘Bayesian’ for fuzzy (Zhang et al. 2012b) and Bayesian identification (Jin et al. 2013). We only demonstrate it with the option ‘bpNewTraining’ with Tibetan moths data set below.

  • Ref< - TibetanMoth

  • out < - sample.ref(ref, sample.porp = 0.85, sample.level = "species")

  • ref2 < - out$ref.selected

  • que < - out$ref.left

  • bsi< - barcoding.spe.identify(ref2, que, method = "bpNewTraining")

The output is shown in Appendix S3.

barcoding.spe.identify2

This function is initially specially designed for non-protein-coding barcodes; however, it is able to deal with standard COI barcodes as well. In the latter, the only thing you need to consider is the choice of kmer length if you do not use an empirical value. In the following, we demonstrate its usage for ITS barcodes of pine moth species (Dai et al. 2012).

  • ref < - pineMothITS1

  • out < - sample.ref(ref, sample.porp = 0.85, sample.level = "species")

  • ref2 < - out$ref.selected

  • que < - out$ref.left

  • bsi2 < - barcoding.spe.identify2(ref2, que, kmer = 10, optimization = "TRUE")

The output is shown in Appendix S4.

barcoding.gap

  • b.gap < - barcoding.gap(ref = pineMothCOI, dist = "K80")

Besides issuing a plot of distribution of intraspecific and interspecific genetic distances, the function also outputs basic statistics of inter- and intraspecific distances, including corresponding minimum, maximum, median and mean values.

barcodes.eval

  • b.eval < - barcodes.eval(pineMothCOI, pineMothITS1, kmer1 = 3, kmer2 = 3)

The function returns χ2 value (3·70), barcoding success rate of species identification for each barcode (0·9142 for COI barcode, 0·8115 for ITS1) and significance P value (0·0271) that indicates significant larger species identification success rates for COI barcode than ITS1 in this case.

compare2delimitations

This function can be useful in case you would like to see the comparison between two sorts of delimitations/identifications, for instance morphological and molecular delimitation/identification (MOTU).

  • ref < - pineMothCOI

  • set.seed(7)

  • out < - sample.ref(ref, sample.porp = 0.85, sample.level = "species")

  • ref2 < - out$ref.selected

  • que < - out$ref.left

  • bsi2 < - barcoding.spe.identify(ref2, que, method = "fuzzyId")

  • que.morph < - gsub(".+","", rownames(que))

  • compare.morph.mole < - compare2delimitations(deli1 = que.morph, deli2 = bsi2$output_identified$spe.Identified)

  • compare.morph.mole

consensus.identify

In the following, we show a consensus identification of a query data set randomly drawn from Tibetan moth species data set (Jin et al. 2013) with three different methods, including BP-based (Zhang et al. 2008), fuzzy-set based (Zhang et al. 2012b) and Bayesian identification (Jin et al. 2013, Table 3).

  • ref < - TibetanMoth

  • set.seed(7)

  • out < - sample.ref(ref,sample.porp=0.95,sample.level="species")

  • ref2 < - out$ref.selected

  • que < - out$ref.left

  • bsi0 < - barcoding.spe.identify(ref2, que, method = "bpNewTrainingOnly")

  • bsi1 < - barcoding.spe.identify(ref2, que, method = "bpUseTrained")

  • bsi2 < - barcoding.spe.identify(ref2, que, method = "fuzzyId")

  • bsi3 < - barcoding.spe.identify(ref2, que, method = "Bayesian")

  • que.IDs < - gsub(",.+","",rownames(que))

  • bpid < - bsi1$output_identified$spe.Identified

  • fuzzyid < - bsi2$output_identified$spe.Identified

  • Bayesianid < - bsi3$output_identified$output_identified

  • identifications < - data.frame(queIDs = que.IDs, pid = bpid, fuzzyid = fuzzyid, Bayesianid = Bayesianid)

  • ccs < - consensus.identify(identifications)

Distributions

BarcodingR provides several species identification approaches using DNA barcodes, including BP-based (Zhang et al. 2008; Zhang & Savolainen 2009), fuzzy-set based (Zhang et al. 2012b) and methods/functions for non-protein-coding markers, that are not readily available in other packages, such as spider (Brown et al. 2012), or not in an open sources, user-friendly program (Zhang & Savolainen 2009).

BarcodingR is freely available from https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/BarcodingR/index.html or https://github.com/zhangab2008/BarcodingR.git. Source code and manuals in PDF are also on github from https://github.com/zhangab2008/BarcodingR.git and Appendix S5. All releases will be distributed on Microsoft Windows, Mac OSX and Linux platform.

A.B.Z. designed the study, and M.D.H., C.Q.Y. and Z.Y.S. conducted the data analyses. A.B.Z. wrote most codes. M.D.H. and C.Q.Y. wrote part of codes and tested all codes and examples. A.B.Z. and M.D.H. wrote the first draft, and all authors contributed to revisions.
